Round Lake is a small (33-acre) bowl-shaped lake, with a maximum depth of 37 feet. Round is located within the city of Eden Prairie, which owns parkland surrounding the entire lake. In addition to a boat ramp, there is a fishing pier for anglers. Boaters may use electric motors only.

Bluegill sunfish are the dominant species in Round Lake, comprising 93% of fish sampled during this assessment. The average length of bluegill sampled was 7.3 inches. Eighty three percent of bluegill were greater than 7 inches in length, with the largest measuring 8.5 inches. The average weight of bluegill was about 1/3 lb.

Black crappie were less abundant than the bluegill; however, they were of good size. Only 1.8% of the catch was crappie, and their length ranged between 9.0 and 10.8 inches. The average weight for crappie was about 0.5 lb.

Fall electrofishing revealed a marginal largemouth bass fishery, with the largest fish measuring 12.3 inches. Only 8.7% of the bass sampled were over 12 inches, and the average-sized bass was about 7 inches long.

Also sampled in lower numbers were pumpkinseed and hybrid sunfishes, as well as black bullhead. In the past, a variety of fish had been stocked into Round, including walleye, rainbow trout, brook trout, and hybrid (tiger) muskellunge. Because these fish have not appeared in any sampling since 2000, it is assumed that none remain. No fish stocking has occurred since 1992.

Round Lake is a small (33 acre), lake class 30 lake with 70% less than 15ft. in depth. It is located within the city limits of Eden Prairie, Hennepin County. The city owns park land which surrounds the entire lake, which includes a boat ramp and a fishing pier for public use. Many species have been stocked over the years (starting in 1979), the most recent being tiger muskellunge in 1988 and 1992. No stocking of any species has occurred since.

Bluegill were found to be the dominant species within Round Lake, consistent with previous surveys. With a mean length of 6.56 inches, 87% of the bluegills sampled were greater than 6.0 inches. Bluegills of this survey represented 92% of the total catch from both gillnets and trapnets.

Black crappie comprised about 3% of species sampled in trapnets, ranging in length from 5.0-10.0 inches in length. About 93% of the black crappie sampled were larger than 7.5 inches.

Pumpkinseed were seen in about average numbers, but with above-average weights. They ranged in length from 5.0-7.5 inches, evenly distributed.

Green and hybrid sunfish are present in Round Lake, in comparable numbers to the last survey. Together, they totaled about 4% of the catch/ net, and ranged in length from 5.0-7.5 inches.

Black bullheads were also found, and while their numbers are average this lake, their weights were found to be well above average. Black bullheads represent about 2% of the total catch for this survey.

The present fish population of Round Lake is dominated by slow growing bluegills averaging only 6.0 inches in length. Individuals up to 7.8 inches were present in the bluegill sample. Other panfish species present include pumpkinseed, green sunfish, hybrid sunfish and black crappie.Largemouth bass remain the most abundant game fish in the lake. The average size bass sampled was just ove 12 inches in length and 0.9 pounds per fish. Hybrid Muskellunge and walleye were also captured during this assessment, but in relatively low numbers. Black bullhead averaging over 11.0 inches in length were also observed in the catch.

Round Lake is a small (33 acre) lake located within the city limits of Eden Prarie. The city owns park land which surrounds the entire lake. In addition to a boat ramp, there is a fishing pier for anglers to use. The lake contains a large number of small panfish, mainly bluegills. Average size is 5.7 inches, and only 3% are over 7 inches. Black crappie appear in densities typical of this type of lake, and their average size is 8.6 inches. Many small largemouth bass were sampled in the most recent survey, although a 17.1 inch individual was also captured. Tiger muskellunge are stocked every third year, although none were captured in the most recent survey. Two large walleye, remnants from stockings in 1985-86, were also captured. Also present are pumpkinseed, green, and hybrid sunfish, as well as black bullhead. Pumpkinseed abundance is higher than is typical in this type of lake, while other species have more normal abundances.
